    <statement><p>Add or subtract the rational expressions to a single rational expression and then simplify. If applicable, state the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{x^{2}+5}{x^{2}+x}-\frac{x+5}{x}} =}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>-\frac{6}{x+1}, x\ne 0</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{x^{2}+5}{x^{2}+x}-\frac{x+5}{x}} 
      \amp = {\frac{x^{2}+5}{x\mathopen{}\left(x+1\right)}-\frac{x+5}{x}}  \\
      \amp = {\frac{x^{2}+5}{x\mathopen{}\left(x+1\right)}-\frac{x+5}{x}} \cdot \frac{(x+1)}{(x+1)} \\
      \amp = {\frac{x^{2}+5}{x\mathopen{}\left(x+1\right)}-\frac{\left(x+5\right)\mathopen{}\left(x+1\right)}{x\mathopen{}\left(x+1\right)}} \\
      \amp = {\frac{x^{2}+5-\left(x+5\right)\mathopen{}\left(x+1\right)}{x\mathopen{}\left(x+1\right)}} \\
      \amp = {\frac{x^{2}+5-\left(x^{2}+6x+5\right)}{x\mathopen{}\left(x+1\right)}} \\
      \amp = {\frac{x^{2}+5-x^{2}-6x-5}{x\mathopen{}\left(x+1\right)}} \\
      \amp = {-\frac{6x}{x\mathopen{}\left(x+1\right)}} \\
      \amp = {-\frac{6}{x+1}, x\ne 0}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factor <m>{x}</m> was canceled, the domain condition lost during the simplification is <m>x \ne {0}</m>.</p>
</solution>
